<activity xml:id="act-tiempoParaHistoriaEraseOtraVez" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

<title>Tiempo para una historia… érase otra vez</title>

<statement>
  <p>Túrnate con tu pareja para contar una historia que se pueda representar con cada ecuación. Luego, para cada ecuación, escojan una historia, digan qué cantidad describe <m>x</m> y resuelvan la ecuación. Si tienen dificultades, dibujen un diagrama.</p>

  <sidebyside>
    <p>
      <me>\num{0.7} + x = 12</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>\frac{1}{4}x = \frac{3}{2}</me>
    </p>
  </sidebyside>
  
</statement>

<solution>
  <p>[@@@@@@@@@] Answers vary. Sample responses:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>x = \num{11.3}</m>. Diego went to the store to buy a box of crayons, which cost <m>70</m> cents. While there, he picked up some other items. The total amount he paid at checkout was <m>\$12</m>. Solving the equation gives <m>\num{11.3}</m>. Diego spent <m>\$\num{11.3}</m> on the other items he bought at the store.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>x = 6</m>. <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> of a bottle of water contains <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> cups of water. How many cups are in the whole bottle? The solution is <m>\frac{\frac{3}{2}}{\frac{1}{4}}</m>, which is <m>6</m>. One bottle of water contains <m>6</m> cups.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
</solution>


